title: For Sale:  LaRue Tactical RISR for magpul ctr
postcontent:
call or text REDACTED credit cards ok

Perfect for those who don't already own a CTR.
 It's a fact that some AR's need a cheek riser to get proper cheek weld for raised scopes or rifles with raised rails. It's another fact that standard AR charging handles require a lot of travel, making it impossible to charge a rifle without moving a collapsible stock all the way to the rear. The LaRue RISR solves these problems. 

Made in Texas, USA, out of glass-reinforced polymer, the RISR is spring-loaded, and travels to the rear as the charging handle is moved to the rear. When the charging handle is released, the RISR snaps forward. Designed to fit the excellent Magpul CTR butt stock without modification, the RISR only takes a few minutes to install with a phillips-head screwdriver.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1970 Williams "Rock-N-Roll" Pinball Machine
postcontent:
For sale is a very cool and rare 1970 Williams Rock n Roll pinball machine. This is the real deal full size pinball, not a half size or plastic pinball for kids.
This machine is very unique and fun to play; as it has a spinner that spins and gives you a random bonus when the ball lands in the bonus slot.
The machine is in good condition and works great. No broken or cracked plastics. There is some wear to the playfield and cabinet which is expected (if there wasn't it was probably repainted and not original). The backglass does have some flaking in spots, but shouldn't get any worse as it was clear coated with the proper sealer.
The rubber rings and ball were replaced a few years ago, and the playfield was cleaned and triple waxed at that time as well. I believe all the lights work (I will include a few bulbs if there are some burnt out).
In 1970 there were two almost identical machines made: Rock n Roll and Jive Time. The Rock n Roll was the rarer of the two machines as it was the "add-a-ball" version. Add-a-ball games were built for the few states that banned gambling (Wisconsin was one of those few states), as at that time "winning" a free game by matching your final score to a randomly picked number, was considered gambling. Not many of these machines were produced and even fewer survived until today.
Currently the machine is set-up for free play. There are no locks or keys with the machine (I will install a new front door lock and key for an additional $15).
I will included an original Jive Time owners manual to whoever buys the machine.

Asking $550 cash.
Contact me at REDACTED (no emails, I get to many phony emails).

Will help take apart and move.
Actual pictures of the machine for sale are listed on the internet pinball database link below:
http://www.ipdb.org/showpic.pl?id=1981&picno=8264

I have a target Kimber conversion in silver. It has the target sights as well as the front and rear cocking serrations. These are very nice conversions that shoot very well. It has had a barrel extension professionally added and then threaded 1/2-28 concentric to the bore for use with a suppressor. The smith that did the work fired several magazines and it was 100% reliable with no baffle strikes. It is very straight thread job because my can has .234" baffles and bullets pass through those baffles without issue. Most commercial suppressors use a .25" or large baffle so this conversion will work without any worry of baffle strikes.

Round count is in the 300 round range total. It is by far the most accurate 22 pistol I have ever shot, with or without the suppressor. This conversion is 100% reliable with all bulk and supersonic ammo as well as with certain subsonics. The barrel is short enough that most bulk remains subsonic as well.

title: For Sale:  Bushnell Banner? 3-9x40 rifle scope
postcontent:
This is a 3-9x40 rifle scope that came packaged with a Mossberg 100 ATR bolt action rifle. The instruction booklet didn't have any identifiers except "D-TG-IS-03, Delta OEM LLC, 2008". Even Mossberg won't spill the beans when I called, they just replied "we supplied the scope with the rifle. We have a confidentiality agreement with the manufacturer". After posting the pic on 2 web forums, the overwhelming majority concluded that it's a Bushnell Banner model scope, sans the markings and distinctive "B" windage caps. 

That being said, this was used to sight in the barrel and has 12 shots under it (set to 100 yds). It has adjustable magnification from 3x to 9x with a 40mm objective lens. The click adjustment is 1/4 MOA (each click moves the strike of the round 1/4" at 100 yards) for both elevation and windage. It has 2 bungeed caps, the rear cup being amber color for clearer vision. 

I learned to shoot with the mil dot system, so crosshairs just irritate me. My mil dot went on and this came off. It's essentially brand new. No dings, nicks, scratches, etc. 

You get the scope, caps and instructions (mounting rings in the picture are NOT included). Please feel free to ask any questions you may have. 

Serious inquiries only, call or text REDACTED.

This class is an Advanced CCH Class; it is the next logical course of instruction for that that have or are considering carrying a concealed handgun.

I am a CCH Instructor (since 2007) and a full time police officer. In teaching CCH classes, I have seen the need for a more advanced curriculum that goes beyond the CCH law and teaches how to apply CCH to your life - meaning how to effectively carry a handgun (types of carry, options, choices), types of handguns available and why you would choose a particular type, how to deploy a handgun under stress and how to make that choice.

I touch on these topics in my CCH classes, but this curriculum is designed to offer much more detail and hands-on exercises to help you as a CCH holder.

It's not enough to get your license and go to the target range. To be effective in armed defense, you need to skills and knowledge to be effective without being a liability.

I have created this course based on training and experience as both an instructor and law enforcement officer.

In this 4-hour course, you will learn:

Weapon and Holster Selection
Ammunition Choices and Philosophy
The Stages of the Draw
The Importance of Trigger Control and Fundamentals
The Adrenaline Effect
Use of Cover and Movement
Less Lethal Options
Threat Detection, Avoidance and Confrontation
Use of Force - Legal and Moral Issues
The After Effect of combative encounters

This class consists of presentations as well as hands-on exercises. I use the SIRT training pistol as well as simulated non-firing replicas as part of this training regime.
I consider this information to be a 'must have' for anyone carrying or considering carrying a handgun. The state CCH course only goes so far. This is the additional training and information that you need.

Classes forming now, with the next scheduled to be November 12, 2011 (one week after my next CCH class).

Feel free to email with questions or call Six Five Five Six Four Six One just about any time...

Thanks to looking!

title: For Sale:  Rem700 7mm SAUM & accessories
postcontent:
7mm Rem Short Action Ultra Mag (7 SAUM)
24” Pac-Nor fluted barrel, Remington 700 short action. Barreled action done by Leo Schnell. Iron Brigade Armory bedded the barreled action into the McMillan stock.  Iron Brigade trigger guard. Iron Brigade Armory 20 MOA tapered base & rings. Badger bolt handle. McMillan A5 stock w/ adjustable cheek piece. Sling loops. Currently shooting the 162 AMAX bullet. 149 total rounds down the barrel (that includes break-in).  Bullet speed is only 2762 fps so it’s not even breathing hard - with a 100 yd zero the MOA drop at 1000 yds is ~27 MOA (~5400’ elevation). There is A LOT more room to step up the powder charge and get it closer to 3000 fps and hit another accuracy node. The charge was kept low to let the BC of the bullet (.624) do the work and save barrel life.  Last time I had it out earlier this summer I shot 10-12 rounds and was hitting ¾ size clay pigeons at 800 yds, it’s a VERY accurate rifle. I’m getting out of 7mm is the only reason I’m selling  it. I have a couple of “go-to” rifles in the safe and this is one of them, a proven, accurate shooter.  Funds go towards another project rifle. Lots of little goodies included, bullets, cases, dies.
There is some hangar rash from the bolt handle getting rubbed against other rifles in the safe. It’s not pretty. There is also some rash on the bottom of the trigger guard also a couple of marks on the barrel . Pics of the rash included.
500 - 162 grain Hornady AMAX (moly) bullets unopened boxes
